The Born-Haber cycle is an application of Hess's Law, used to calculate the lattice energy of an ionic compound, which cannot be measured directly, or to determine any other unknown enthalpy change in the cycle if all other values are known. It relates the standard enthalpy of formation of an an ionic compound to several steps involving ionization energies, electron affinities, sublimation, and dissociation energies.

\textbf{Addressing the Compound Formula:}

The question asks for a Born-Haber cycle for compound MX, where M is an alkali earth metal and X is a halogen. Alkali earth metals (Group 2) typically form \ch{M^{2+}} ions, while halogens (Group 17) form \ch{X^-} ions. Therefore, the stable ionic compound formed between an alkali earth metal M and a halogen X is \ch{MX2}, not MX. To provide a chemically accurate and rigorous solution consistent with the definitions of M and X, we will construct the Born-Haber cycle for the formation of \ch{MX2}.

\textbf{Description of the Born-Haber Cycle for \ch{MX2}:}

1.  \textbf{Standard Enthalpy of Formation ($\Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}$):} This is the overall reaction where one mole of \ch{MX2}(s) is formed from its constituent elements in their standard states. This is the net energy change the cycle aims to describe.
    \begin{align*}
    \ch{M(s) + X2(g) &\longrightarrow MX2(s)} & \Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}
    \end{align*}

2.  \textbf{Enthalpy of Sublimation of Metal ($\Delta H_{\text{sub}}$):} The energy required to convert one mole of solid metal M into gaseous atoms.
    \begin{align*}
    \ch{M(s) &\longrightarrow M(g)} & \Delta H_{\text{sub}}
    \end{align*}

3.  \textbf{First Ionization Energy ($\text{IE}_1$) of Metal:} The energy required to remove one electron from one mole of gaseous M atoms to form \ch{M^+} gaseous ions.
    \begin{align*}
    \ch{M(g) &\longrightarrow M+(g) + e-} & \text{IE}_1
    \end{align*}

4.  \textbf{Second Ionization Energy ($\text{IE}_2$) of Metal:} The energy required to remove a second electron from one mole of gaseous \ch{M^+} ions to form \ch{M^{2+}} gaseous ions.
    \begin{align*}
    \ch{M+(g) &\longrightarrow M^{2+}(g) + e-} & \text{IE}_2
    \end{align*}
    (The total energy for ionization is $\text{IE}_1 + \text{IE}_2$)

5.  \textbf{Bond Dissociation Energy (D_{\text{X}_2}):} The energy required to break the covalent bond in one mole of gaseous halogen \ch{X2} molecules to form two moles of gaseous X atoms.
    \begin{align*}
    \ch{X2(g) &\longrightarrow 2X(g)} & D_{\text{X}_2}
    \end{align*}

6.  \textbf{First Electron Affinity ($\text{EA}_1$) of Halogen:} The energy change when one mole of gaseous X atoms gains one electron to form one mole of gaseous \ch{X^-} ions. Since two X atoms are involved in forming \ch{MX2}, this step occurs twice.
    \begin{align*}
    \ch{X(g) + e- &\longrightarrow X-(g)} & \text{EA}_1
    \end{align*}
    (The total energy for electron affinity is $2 \times \text{EA}_1$)

7.  \textbf{Lattice Energy (U):} The energy released when one mole of gaseous \ch{M^{2+}} ions combines with two moles of gaseous \ch{X^-} ions to form one mole of solid ionic lattice \ch{MX2}.
    \begin{align*}
    \ch{M^{2+}(g) + 2X-(g) &\longrightarrow MX2(s)} & U
    \end{align*}

\textbf{Born-Haber Cycle Equation (Hess's Law):}

According to Hess's Law, the sum of the enthalpy changes for steps 2 through 7 equals the standard enthalpy of formation ($\Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}$) for \ch{MX2}.

$\Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}(\text{MX}_2) = \Delta H_{\text{sub}}(\text{M}) + \text{IE}_1(\text{M}) + \text{IE}_2(\text{M}) + D_{\text{X}_2} + 2 \times \text{EA}_1(\text{X}) + U(\text{MX}_2)$

