Ligands are molecules or ions that bind to a central metal atom or ion to form a coordination complex. They act as Lewis bases, donating a pair of electrons to the central metal (which acts as a Lewis acid) to form coordinate covalent bonds. The term "ligand" comes from the Latin word \textit{ligare}, meaning "to bind."

Ligands can be classified in several ways, primarily based on their denticity (number of donor atoms) and charge.

\textbf{1. Classification based on Denticity (Number of Donor Atoms):}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Monodentate Ligands:} These ligands possess only one donor atom and form a single coordinate bond with the central metal ion. Examples include water (H$_2$O), ammonia (NH$_3$), chloride ion (Cl$^-$), cyanide ion (CN$^-$), hydroxide ion (OH$^-$), and carbonyl (CO).
    \item \textbf{Bidentate Ligands:} These ligands have two donor atoms and can form two coordinate bonds to the same central metal ion, leading to the formation of a chelate ring. Examples include ethylenediamine (en, H$_2$N--CH$_2$--CH$_2$--NH$_2$), oxalate ion (ox, C$_2$O$_4^{2-}$), and acetylacetonate (acac$^-$).
    \item \textbf{Polydentate Ligands (Chelating Ligands):} These ligands possess more than two donor atoms and can form multiple coordinate bonds to the same central metal ion, forming multiple chelate rings. This phenomenon is known as chelation, and the resulting complexes are often more stable (chelate effect). Examples include diethylenetriamine (dien, a tridentate ligand), triethylenetetramine (trien, a tetradentate ligand), and ethylenediaminetetraacetate (EDTA$^{4-}$, a hexadentate ligand).
    \item \textbf{Bridging Ligands:} These ligands have two or more donor atoms and can coordinate to two or more different central metal ions, thus linking them together in polynuclear complexes. Examples include hydroxide (OH$^-$), chloride (Cl$^-$), and carbonyl (CO).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{2. Classification based on Charge:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Neutral Ligands:} These ligands carry no net charge. Examples include water (H$_2$O), ammonia (NH$_3$), carbon monoxide (CO), and pyridine (C$_5$H$_5$N).
    \item \textbf{Anionic Ligands:} These ligands carry a negative charge. Their names often end in '-o' when coordinating (e.g., chloro for Cl$^-$, cyano for CN$^-$, oxalato for C$_2$O$_4^{2-}$). Examples include chloride (Cl$^-$), cyanide (CN$^-$), hydroxide (OH$^-$), and sulfate (SO$_4^{2-}$).
    \item \textbf{Cationic Ligands:} These are rare but exist, carrying a positive charge. An example is the nitronium ion (NO$^+$).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{3. Special Types of Ligands:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Ambidentate Ligands:} These are monodentate ligands that can coordinate to the central metal ion through two or more different donor atoms, though only one at a time. Examples include the nitrite ion (NO$_2^-$, which can bind via N or O), the thiocyanate ion (SCN$^-$, which can bind via S or N), and the cyanide ion (CN$^-$, which can bind via C or N).
    \item \textbf{Pi-Acceptor Ligands (or $\sigma$-donor/$\pi$-acceptor ligands):} These ligands are good $\sigma$-donors but also have empty $\pi^*$ (antibonding) orbitals that can accept electron density from the filled d-orbitals of the metal. This back-bonding strengthens the metal-ligand bond. Examples include carbon monoxide (CO), cyanide (CN$^-$), and phosphines (PR$_3$).
\end{itemize}

The E/Z nomenclature system is used to describe the geometric isomerism around carbon-carbon double bonds, providing an unambiguous way to designate stereoisomers when the conventional 	extit{cis-trans} system is insufficient. 

	extbf{1. Meaning of E and Z Symbols:}
 egin{itemize}
    \item 	extbf{Z (Zusammen):} German for "together". This configuration is assigned when the two higher-priority groups on each carbon of the double bond are on the 	extit{same side} of the double bond. 
    \item 	extbf{E (Entgegen):} German for "opposite". This configuration is assigned when the two higher-priority groups on each carbon of the double bond are on 	extit{opposite sides} of the double bond.
\end{itemize}

	extbf{2. Cahn-Ingold-Prelog (CIP) Priority Rules (for assigning E/Z):}
To determine which group is higher priority on each carbon of the double bond, the Cahn-Ingold-Prelog (CIP) rules are followed:
 egin{enumerate}
    \item 	extbf{Atomic Number:} The atom directly attached to the double bond carbon with the higher atomic number receives higher priority. 
    \item 	extbf{Next Atoms:} If the first atoms are identical, move outwards along the chain to the next set of atoms until a point of difference is found. The group whose first point of difference contains atoms of higher atomic number receives higher priority. 
    \item 	extbf{Multiple Bonds:} Double or triple bonds are treated as if the atoms are bonded to an equivalent number of identical single-bonded phantom atoms. For example, a C$=$O group is treated as a carbon bonded to two oxygen atoms; a C$\equiv$C group is treated as a carbon bonded to three other carbons.
\end{enumerate}

	extbf{3. Advantages of E/Z System over Conventional 	extit{cis-trans} System:}
The 	extit{cis-trans} system is limited because it can only be applied effectively when there are two identical or very similar substituents on each carbon of the double bond (e.g., 1,2-disubstituted alkenes, or cases where the two hydrogens are being compared). For example, in 2-butene, where both carbons have a methyl group and a hydrogen, 	extit{cis} (methyls on same side) and 	extit{trans} (methyls on opposite sides) are clear. 

The E/Z system offers the following advantages:
 egin{itemize}
    \item 	extbf{Universal Applicability:} It can be used for 	extit{any} alkene with restricted rotation around the double bond, including tri-substituted and tetra-substituted alkenes, where the 	extit{cis-trans} system often fails or becomes ambiguous. 
    \item 	extbf{Unambiguous Designation:} By using an objective set of priority rules (CIP rules) based on atomic numbers, the E/Z system provides an unambiguous designation for the geometric isomer, regardless of the complexity or dissimilarity of the substituents. 
\end{itemize}

	extbf{4. Assignment of E and Z Configuration to the Given Molecules:}
For each molecule, we first identify the substituents on each carbon of the double bond, assign priorities using CIP rules, and then define the E and Z configurations based on the relative positions of the high-priority groups.

