\subsection*{Differentiation between Bonding and Antibonding Molecular Orbitals}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Bonding Molecular Orbital (BMO):}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Formation:} Formed by the constructive interference (in-phase overlap) of atomic orbitals, where wave functions add up.\
        $\psi_{\text{BMO}} = \psi_{\text{A}} + \psi_{\text{B}}$
        \item \textbf{Energy:} Lower energy than the constituent atomic orbitals, leading to molecular stability.
        \item \textbf{Electron Density:} Increased electron density in the internuclear region.
        \item \textbf{Stability:} Stabilizes the molecule.
        \item \textbf{Nodal Plane:} Typically no nodal plane perpendicular to the internuclear axis between the nuclei.
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Antibonding Molecular Orbital (ABMO):}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Formation:} Formed by the destructive interference (out-of-phase overlap) of atomic orbitals, where wave functions subtract.\
        $\psi_{\text{ABMO}} = \psi_{\text{A}} - \psi_{\text{B}}$
        \item \textbf{Energy:} Higher energy than the constituent atomic orbitals, leading to molecular instability.
        \item \textbf{Electron Density:} Decreased electron density in the internuclear region, with a nodal plane perpendicular to the internuclear axis.
        \item \textbf{Stability:} Destabilizes the molecule.
        \item \textbf{Nodal Plane:} Always possesses at least one nodal plane perpendicular to the internuclear axis between the nuclei.
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Drawing the molecular orbitals formed by overlapping two '$p_z$' orbitals}

Assume the internuclear axis is the z-axis.

\begin{enumerate}[(i)]
    \item \textbf{'$p_z$ orbital' overlapping with '$p_z$ orbital':}

    \subsubsection*{Initial Atomic Orbitals ($p_z$):}
    Each $p_z$ orbital consists of two lobes of opposite phase (e.g., positive and negative) oriented along the z-axis. When two such orbitals approach each other along the z-axis, head-on overlap occurs, leading to sigma ($\sigma$) molecular orbitals.

    \subsubsection*{Bonding Molecular Orbital ($\sigma_{p_z}$):}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Formation:} Achieved through constructive interference, where the positive lobe of one $p_z$ orbital overlaps with the positive lobe of the other, and the negative lobes similarly overlap. This is an in-phase interaction.
        \item \textbf{Description:} The resulting $\sigma_{p_z}$ orbital is characterized by a significant accumulation of electron density directly between the two nuclei along the z-axis. It appears as an elongated, somewhat elliptical region of electron density encompassing both nuclei, with slight extensions outwards along the z-axis. It is cylindrically symmetrical around the internuclear axis. There is no nodal plane between the nuclei. The electron density is concentrated in the bonding region.
    \end{itemize}

    \subsubsection*{Antibonding Molecular Orbital ($\sigma^{*}_{p_z}$):}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Formation:} Formed by destructive interference, where the positive lobe of one $p_z$ orbital overlaps with the negative lobe of the other $p_z$ orbital. This is an out-of-phase interaction.
        \item \textbf{Description:} The resulting $\sigma^{*}_{p_z}$ orbital features a clear nodal plane situated exactly between the two nuclei, perpendicular to the internuclear axis. This plane represents a region of zero electron density. The electron density is concentrated in two distinct, roughly dumbbell-shaped lobes located on the outer sides of the nuclei, away from the internuclear region. This orbital is also cylindrically symmetrical around the internuclear axis, but with the critical nodal plane separating the two primary regions of electron density. The electron density is pushed away from the bonding region, hence its antibonding nature.
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

